Introduction¶

The dataset description:
The data is related with direct marketing campaigns of a Portuguese banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required, in order to access if the product (bank term deposit) would be ('yes') or not ('no') subscribed.

Meaning of variables:

bank client data:
1 - age (numeric)
2 - job : type of job (categorical: 'admin.','blue-collar','entrepreneur','housemaid','management','retired','self-employed','services','student','technician','unemployed','unknown')
3 - marital : marital status (categorical: 'divorced','married','single','unknown'; note: 'divorced' means divorced or widowed)
4 - education (categorical: 'basic.4y','basic.6y','basic.9y','high.school','illiterate','professional.course','university.degree','unknown')
5 - default: has credit in default? (categorical: 'no','yes','unknown')
6 - housing: has housing loan? (categorical: 'no','yes','unknown')
7 - loan: has personal loan? (categorical: 'no','yes','unknown')
related with the last contact of the current campaign:
8 - contact: contact communication type (categorical: 'cellular','telephone')
9 - month: last contact month of year (categorical: 'jan', 'feb', 'mar', ..., 'nov', 'dec')
10 - day_of_week: last contact day of the week (categorical: 'mon','tue','wed','thu','fri')
11 - duration: last contact duration, in seconds (numeric). Important note: this attribute highly affects the output target
(e.g., if duration=0 then y='no'). Yet, the duration is not known before a call is performed. Also, after the end of the call y is obviously known. Thus, this input should only be included for benchmark purposes and should be discarded if the intention is to have a realistic predictive model.
other attributes:
12 - campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact)
13 - pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric; 999 means client was not previously contacted)
14 - previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (numeric)
15 - poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (categorical: 'failure','nonexistent','success')
social and economic context attributes
16 - emp.var.rate: employment variation rate - quarterly indicator (numeric)
17 - cons.price.idx: consumer price index - monthly indicator (numeric)
18 - cons.conf.idx: consumer confidence index - monthly indicator (numeric)
19 - euribor3m: euribor 3 month rate - daily indicator (numeric)
20 - nr.employed: number of employees - quarterly indicator (numeric)
target variable
21 - y - has the client subscribed a term deposit? (binary: 'yes','no')

Target variable:
1 - client bought term deposit
0 - client did not bought term deposit

Problem description:
Build and evaluate classification model to predict whether the client will subscribe to a term deposit.

Programming language:
Python

Libraries:
Scikit-learn, SciPy, Statsmodels, Pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib, Seaborn, Scikitplot, Yellowbrick

Algorithms:
Notmal test, dummy coding, SMOTE, RFE, VIF, Logit, Logistic Regression

Methods of model evaluation
Confusion Matrix, ROC curve, AUC, Accumulative protif curve, Forecasting error of classes, Classification Report and indicators: Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F1

3. Exploration Data Analysis (EDA) and visualizations¶

  • Classes are imbalanced, and the ratio of no-subscription to subscription instances is 88.7% to 11.3%.
  • The frequency of purchase of the deposit depends a great deal on the job title. Thus, the job title can be a good predictor of the outcome variable.
  • The marital status does not seem a strong predictor for the outcome variable.
  • Education seems a good predictor of the outcome variable.
  • Day of week may not be a good predictor of the outcome.
  • Month might be a good predictor of the outcome variable.
  • Most of the customers of the bank in this dataset are in the age range of 3040.
  • Poutcome seems to be a good predictor of the outcome variable.

Target variable - y¶

Classes are imbalanced and the ratio of no-subscription to subscription instances is 88.7% to 11.3%.

By fat he most interested in buying a term deposit are pople with whom contact in previous attempt failed. A lot of people are interested in buing again. The least interested are people how were not interested in during previous contact.

***Most of analysed customers come from the category "nonexistent" means that company has to thoroughly analyze and change hours of contact with clients via call center. Moreover, a lot of previous contacts were failure compared to success. It is advisable to additionally motivate employees or organize additional training to increase their effectiveness of sales.

4. Analysis of normal distribution¶

This function tests the null hypothesis that a sample comes from a normal distribution. For variables with p_value > alpha variable takes a normal distribution.

H0 = the variable comes from a normal distribution
H1 = the variable does not come from a normal distribution

Adopted materiality level alpha = 0.05

No variable comes from a normal distribution.

4.1 Verification based on statistical test and hypotheses¶

In [40]:
#Select numerical variables from the dataset
data_numerical = data[["age", "duration", "campaign", "pdays", "previous",
                       "emp_var_rate", "cons_price_idx", "cons_conf_idx",
                       "euribor3m", "nr_employed"]]
#Verification of hypotheses
results = []
for feature in data_numerical.columns:
    alpha = 0.05
    p_value = scipy.stats.normaltest(data_numerical[feature])[1]
    results.append([feature, p_value])
    if(p_value < alpha):
        print("For variable \"" + feature +
              "\" I reject the zero hypothesis.\n The variable DOES NOT HAVE normal distribution. P-value:", p_value)
    else:
        print("For variable \"" + feature +
              "\" no grounds for rejecting the zero hypothesis have been detected. The variable HAS normal distribution. P-value:", p_value)

4.2 Verification based on kurtosis and skew¶

Normal distribution parameters should be:

  • kurtosis = 0
  • skew = 0

Kurtosis is a measure of flattening the decomposition. It tells how flattened (negative values of kurtosis) or bloated (positive values of kurtosis) the distribution of the examined variable is in relation to normal distribution.

Interpretation of skew:

  • A factor of 0 is a symmetrical distribution.
  • A negative coefficient is a left-sided oblique distribution (elongated left arm of the distribution; mean less than the median).
  • A factor with a positive value is a right-hand slanted distribution (elongated right arm of the distribution; mean greater than the median).
In [42]:
#Calculation of kurtosis and skew for each numerical variables by aggregation method
data_numerical.agg(["kurtosis", "skew"])
Out[42]:
age duration campaign pdays previous emp_var_rate cons_price_idx cons_conf_idx euribor3m nr_employed
kurtosis 0.791312 20.247938 36.979795 22.229463 20.108816 -1.062632 -0.829809 -0.358558 -1.406803 -0.003760
skew 0.784697 3.263141 4.762507 -4.922190 3.832042 -0.724096 -0.230888 0.303180 -0.709188 -1.044262

According to the assumptions of normal distribution, the mean value and the median should be very close (preferably equal) to each other. Then there is a chance to suspect the distribution of the variable of lack of diagonality.

Differences in values show that distribution is skewed:

  • mean < median --> left oblique distribution (elongated left arm of distribution)
  • mean > median --> right oblique distribution (elongated right arm of distribution)

6. Dummying¶

In linear models, we should be careful about the problem of collinearity. When placing all categories of a given variable in the model there is a perfect collinearity. Therefore, we should remove one category each of those variables that have been saved in more than one column. In this case drop_first = True parameter was used.

In [50]:
#List of categorical variables from the dataset
categorical_variables=["job","marital","education","default","housing",
                       "loan","contact","month","day_of_week","poutcome"]

#Dummy coding in categorical varaibles, change of name of new variable and drop the first category from each dummy variable
for variables in categorical_variables:
    categories_list="var"+"_"+variables
    categories_list = pd.get_dummies(data[variables],
                                     prefix=variables,
                                     drop_first=True)
    data1=data.join(categories_list)
    data=data1
    
#Variables after dummying
data_vars=data.columns.tolist()
to_keep=[i for i in data_vars if i not in categorical_variables]

7. Oversampling with SMOTE¶

Now there is a perfect balanced dataset. Only training dataset was over-sampled, because by oversampling only on the training data, none of the information in the test dataset is being used to create synthetic observations, therefore, no information will bleed from test dataset into the model training.

9.1.2 VIF calculation¶

VIF - variance inflation factor, assessing the degree of collinearity of explanatory variables in statistical models.

  • VIF=1 : no collinearity of explanatory variables
  • 1<VIF<10 : there is a slight collinearity of explanatory variables, it is worth considering a change of model
  • VIF>10 : there is a strong collinearity of explanatory variables, you should remove the variable from the model

Calculated values of VIF are low and 1 variable: month_oct only minimally exceeding the value of 1. There is no collinearity of explanatory variables.

In [57]:
#Function to calculate VIF indicator for selected seatures
def calculation_VIF(X):
    """
    Building DataFrame with fetures selected to model (parameter X)
    and calculating of VIF indicator for them.
    """
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["selected features"] = X.columns
    vif["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i) for i in range(X.shape[1])]
    vif["VIF"] = round(vif['VIF'], 2)
    vif = vif.sort_values(by = "VIF", ascending = False)
    return(vif)

#Activation of function to calculate VIF for selected features
calculation_VIF(X)

9.2.2 ROC curve¶

Receiver Operating Characteristic illustrates the relationship between the percentage of true positive results (sensitivity) and the percentage of false positive results (inverse specificity).
Graph should be convex to the left upper corner. The more accurate the model, the more the curve is shifted left and up. The diagonal represents a classifier generating random results. Field under the curve is an indicator describing the efficiency of the model.

ROC curve has similar shape on test and train dataset. It means that probably there is no overfitting. Result is really good, so there is also no underfitting. Rest indicators concerning test and train datasets will be compared later to make sure that there is no over/underfitting.

In [61]:
#Function to plot ROC - used to plot ROC curve in model 2 and model 3
def roc_plot(model, x_test_or_train_dataset, y_test_or_train_dataset, kind_dataset):
    """
    Building ROC curve based on arguments: model, x from test or train dataset, y from test or train 
    dataset, kind of dataset: test or train.
    """
    y_pred_proba = model.predict_proba(x_test_or_train_dataset)[::,1]
    fpr, tpr, _ = metrics.roc_curve(y_test_or_train_dataset, y_pred_proba)
    auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test_or_train_dataset, y_pred_proba)
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label="Logistic Regression (auc = %0.2f)" % auc, color="black")
    plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate",color="grey", fontsize = 18)
    plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate",color="grey", fontsize = 18)
    #Condition for kind of dataset
    if kind_dataset == "test":
        plt.title("Test dataset - ROC", fontsize=25)
    elif kind_dataset == "train":
        plt.title("Train dataset - ROC", fontsize=25)
    #Setting legend
    plt.legend(loc=4, 
               fontsize=15,
               prop={"size": 14},
               title="Area Under Curve",
               title_fontsize="16",
               frameon=True)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],"r--")

9.2.4 Accumulative protif curve¶

The binary classifier can be evaluated using the accumulated profit curve, which illustrates the relationship between the percentage of true positive results (sensitivity) and the percentage of positive forecasts. The purpose of this curve is to sort all classifications according to the predicted probability. On the horizontal axis there is a percentage of the forecast positive results. Vertical axis represents sensitivity (percentage of results truly positive).

If we rank clients according to their probability of buy deposit and select those whose chances are no more than 20%, it will turn out that this is 40% of all clients.

  • chances of buy deposit by client no greater than 20% -----> 40% of clients
  • chances of buy deposit by client no greater than 40% -----> 75% of clients
  • chances of buy deposit by client no greater than 60% -----> 95% of clients
In [64]:

ax.set_xlabel("Percentage of sample", fontsize=25)

Class forecasting error - the upper part of the left bar represents the number of clients who did not buy term deposit, but were expected to buy (false positive), the lower part of the right-hand bar represents the number the buying clients, however, were expected to not buy (result falsely negative).

9.2.6 Classifivation report¶

  • accuracy - Percentage of correct forecasts.
  • precision - Ability to find only the right samples. Percentage of correct positive forecasts (PP divided by [PP + FP]). (How accurate are the results?).
  • recall - Ability to search only positive samples. percentage of positively classified positive results. (How many successful results were returned?).
  • f1 - Harmonic average of precision and sensitivity.

13. Conclusions¶

General summary

The main target of this project was to build and evaluate classification model to predict whether the client will subscribe to a term deposit. Logistic Regression model was used to perform the prediction.
Data was explored and visualized. Moreover, analysis of normal distiburion, outliers removal, dummy coding, oversampling by SMOTE and features selection by RFE were performed. Then selected variables were evaluate based on p-value and VIF and model was build and evaluated.

EDA (Exploratory Data Analysis) summary

Dataset contains 41188 observations as well as 21 variables including target variable (y). After outliers removal the dataset has 32050 observations and 21 features.
The dataset does not contain missing variables.
Data was cleaned and then grouped and visualized. Data was also explore in terms of model suitability based on the variability of values in variable.

Modelling summary

After analysis of normal distiburion, outliers removal, dummy coding, oversampling by SMOTE and features selection by RFE selected features were evaluated based on p-value and VIF indicator. All selected values were finally used in model biulding.
The dataset was splitted by train (70%) and test (30%) dataset. Furtermore, stratify parameter was used to the target variable was presented in proportion to the main dataseet.
Model was evaluated by: Confusion Matrix, ROC curve, AUC, Accumulative protif curve, Forecasting error of classes, Classification Report and indicators: Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F1
Results of train and test datasets were compared. In this way was confirmed that there is no overfitting or underfitting.
Model presents really good results with for instance Accuracy = 0.89.
